Rating: 3
This bean dip is tasty - or rather a spin on this dip that I concocted based on what I had on hand and previous reviewers' tips. I used 2 cans of cannelli beans, drained. I sauteed them in a pan with a sprig of rosemary and two garlic cloves (since I don't like onions). I added about a half teaspoon of red pepper flakes and a three or four tablespoons of olive oil, as well as salt to taste. I used 1/2 cup dry sundried tomatoes and soaked them in hot water for a few minutes before adding them and the bean mixture as well as a teaspoon chopped fresh rosemary, the juice of one lemon, 2 tablespoons of olive oil and 1/3 cup water to the blender and pureed. I served with sliced jalapeno bread and toasted pita wedges. The guests ate it up!

Rating: 4
I used canned beans and it came out perfect. Raves every time I make this. Everyone asks for the recipe. I use 2 cans of great northern beans sauteed with a little olive oil, 1/2 an onion and a whole sprig of rosemary. Let that cool. While that is cooling, in a food processor, I pulse the rest of the ingredients. I only use half the sundried tomatoes for 2 cans of beans though. Then I add the cooked bean mixture to the processor minus the cooked piece of rosemary, add the water and voila! Awesome everytime.

